contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:20.360 --> 00:22.761
I like to improvise.

00:22.960 --> 00:24.485
I always think I like
to do things

00:24.640 --> 00:27.849
as though I'm...
I'm playing jazz.

00:28.000 --> 00:29.889
Try this, try that.

00:30.720 --> 00:34.167
Okay, the sneakers
from Home Shopping.

00:34.320 --> 00:36.243
I design them and I sell them.

00:36.400 --> 00:40.041
Ordinary black denim jeans.
I'm a denim freak.

00:40.200 --> 00:41.884
Reminded me of a railroad man.

00:42.040 --> 00:44.691
When I was a kid,
I was a railroad buff.

00:44.840 --> 00:47.161
These bracelets
come from Harlem.

00:47.320 --> 00:48.890
These I have such a long time,

00:49.040 --> 00:50.485
I don't even remember
where they came from,

00:50.640 --> 00:52.847
but they were like
slivers of black,

00:53.000 --> 00:54.126
so I love them.

00:55.960 --> 00:58.691
And then these are just things
I've been collecting

00:58.840 --> 01:00.330
over the years.

01:01.360 --> 01:02.407
AnyWaY-

01:02.560 --> 01:03.925
Another mad outfit.

01:04.120 --> 01:07.283
These are my shoes,
smoking slippers.

01:07.440 --> 01:10.410
Suede, embroidered.

01:10.560 --> 01:14.645
This kind of tunic
is from the Mao people,

01:14.840 --> 01:16.604
Chinese minority.

01:16.800 --> 01:19.041
It had a big hood,
and I didn't like the hood,

01:19.200 --> 01:20.850
so I made it into a collar.

01:21.000 --> 01:25.085
And this is part
of my collection of amber.

01:25.240 --> 01:27.971
And then bracelets
from all over the place,

01:28.120 --> 01:29.963
including these ladybugs.

01:30.480 --> 01:32.369
Okay?

01:39.720 --> 01:41.722
I like to put
things together like this.

01:41.880 --> 01:47.410
This is an old jacket
from, uh... Ungaro.

01:47.800 --> 01:49.325
I love the way it's lined.

01:49.480 --> 01:53.121
And these are Gianni Versace
trousers.

01:53.680 --> 01:55.250
So they're kind of fun together.

01:55.400 --> 01:57.721
I'll wear them
with a black turtleneck.

01:57.960 --> 01:59.530
Just has to feel right with me.

01:59.720 --> 02:01.802
Every time I do it,
I do a different way.

02:01.960 --> 02:05.646
I like individuality.

02:06.040 --> 02:09.362
So lost these days.
There's so much sameness.

02:09.560 --> 02:12.291
Everything is homogenized.
I hate it.

02:14.880 --> 02:16.245
Whatever.

02:34.840 --> 02:36.410
- Albert?
- Yes?

02:36.560 --> 02:38.085
Do you think we're demented?

02:41.040 --> 02:42.246
So easy to amuse me.

02:42.400 --> 02:45.449
I get more kick out of this
that costs $4 and change

02:45.640 --> 02:49.122
than if my husband took me
to Harry Winston.

02:49.800 --> 02:51.802
People interview me
and they keeping asking me

02:51.960 --> 02:54.008
about all these rules,
and I say

02:54.160 --> 02:56.003
I don't have any rules
because I would

02:56.160 --> 02:58.731
only be breaking them,
so it's a waste of time.

02:58.880 --> 03:01.531
With me, it's not intellectual.
It's all gut.

03:01.680 --> 03:03.444
I see something,
"Oh, that'll go with this."

03:03.600 --> 03:04.965
I'll try it on.

03:05.160 --> 03:06.446
It's totally,
totally the involvement

03:06.600 --> 03:08.125
and the process.

03:08.280 --> 03:09.566
It's the process
I like much better

03:09.720 --> 03:11.006
even than wearing it.

03:12.760 --> 03:14.922
What could you do
on these three pieces?

03:15.080 --> 03:17.845
Fifteen, 25, 30.

03:18.000 --> 03:19.411
How about $25 for all three?

03:20.560 --> 03:21.766
Can you do $20?

03:21.920 --> 03:24.446
Mm, all right, why not?

03:28.360 --> 03:31.569
I think it was
some very famous clothes horse

03:31.720 --> 03:34.007
said the best thing
was getting dressed.

03:34.160 --> 03:35.810
She didn't give a damn
about going to the party

03:35.960 --> 03:37.041
or being at the party.

03:37.200 --> 03:38.929
It was getting dressed
for the party.

03:39.080 --> 03:41.447
And there's more truth
and poetry in that.

03:54.040 --> 03:58.011
We are so pleased
to have Iris Apfel.

03:58.160 --> 04:01.642
This event will show you
how she works

04:01.840 --> 04:04.525
with people, their bodies,

04:04.720 --> 04:07.405
and the way they should look
or the way they can look.

04:07.600 --> 04:10.285
What brings you
to our fair shore?

04:10.440 --> 04:12.966
I want something that
represents my personality

04:13.120 --> 04:16.680
but is also classic,
so I need help.

04:16.839 --> 04:19.241
There's somebody I've had
my eye on.

04:19.440 --> 04:21.920
You, you, with the earrings.
Come here, girl.

04:25.680 --> 04:27.921
- Oh.
- Oh, wowie-wow.

04:29.520 --> 04:31.363
This was a Gaultier.

04:31.520 --> 04:34.842
I thought it needed a belt.
So we added the belt.

04:35.040 --> 04:39.329
The shawl is also an add-on,
but look at those shoes.

04:39.480 --> 04:40.686
She looks very Vogue-y.

04:42.400 --> 04:43.925
This was something that
when lris picked it out,

04:44.080 --> 04:45.764
I thought she was a little...

04:45.920 --> 04:47.206
I thought her 90 years
was showing.

04:47.360 --> 04:49.124
I never would
have worn this myself.

04:49.280 --> 04:51.009
I would have looked at it
on the rack and kept going.

04:51.160 --> 04:52.321
But I love it.

04:52.520 --> 04:55.683
This is my wild child.

04:55.840 --> 05:00.687
She told me that sometimes
she has to go to occasions

05:00.840 --> 05:03.241
where she has to be
a bit more sophisticated.

05:03.400 --> 05:05.050
And I thought,
now that's a challenge,

05:05.240 --> 05:08.926
to make her look sophisticated
and kooky at the same time

05:09.120 --> 05:11.122
is not the easiest thing
in the world.

05:11.280 --> 05:12.930
But we'll give it a try,

05:13.120 --> 05:15.122
so see if you think
we've succeeded.

05:15.280 --> 05:17.647
Francis, my gosh.

05:20.680 --> 05:22.409
Wow.

05:23.320 --> 05:25.049
Dress looks pure couture.

05:25.200 --> 05:27.521
The necklace I think
is Missoni.

05:27.720 --> 05:30.166
The necklace is spoken for.
I'm buying it.

05:33.080 --> 05:34.844
Okay, baby.
I think you're in.

05:35.000 --> 05:36.365
Thank you.

05:39.400 --> 05:41.721
I was very much influenced
by my mother,

05:41.880 --> 05:45.248
and my mother worshipped
at the altar of the accessory.

05:45.400 --> 05:47.243
My mother could do tricks
with a scarf

05:47.400 --> 05:49.402
that I've never seen
anybody else do.

05:49.560 --> 05:52.928
It was during Depression days
that I grew up,

05:53.120 --> 05:58.809
and my mother always said,
"Buy a good, simple

05:59.000 --> 06:00.604
little black dress

06:00.760 --> 06:03.331
and you'll always have
something to wear

06:03.480 --> 06:06.450
because you can dress it up
or you can dress it down."

06:07.240 --> 06:10.562
Thank you for sharing
your vision.

06:10.760 --> 06:14.048
And on behalf of Loehmann's
90th year,

06:14.200 --> 06:17.249
we would like to celebrate
your 90th birthday, too.

06:18.720 --> 06:21.007
Oh, what a pretty cake!
What a pretty cake!

06:21.160 --> 06:23.049
Oh, my God.

06:34.600 --> 06:37.171
Looked like the eternal flame.

06:38.960 --> 06:41.930
I had discovered Loehmann's,
it was in Brooklyn.

06:42.080 --> 06:45.289
That was when Mrs. Loehmann,
the original...

06:45.440 --> 06:47.363
who was absolutely a trip.

06:47.520 --> 06:50.091
She looked like something
out of Toulouse-Lautrec.

06:50.240 --> 06:53.084
And she would sit
on a high stool

06:53.240 --> 06:55.720
like she was observing
a tennis match.

06:55.880 --> 06:58.770
And she would look at what
everybody in the shop was doing.

06:58.920 --> 07:00.331
And she used to fixate on me,

07:00.520 --> 07:02.409
and she really made me
very uncomfortable.

07:02.560 --> 07:05.689
And one day, she called me over,
and she said,

07:05.840 --> 07:08.320
"Young lady,
I've been watching you."

07:08.480 --> 07:10.209
She said, "Don't anybody...

07:10.360 --> 07:12.966
You're not pretty,
and you'll never be pretty.

07:13.160 --> 07:15.925
But it doesn't matter.
You have something much better.

07:16.120 --> 07:17.610
You have style."

07:21.840 --> 07:23.444
Iris is an artist.

07:23.600 --> 07:26.444
What she uses all of her
clothing

07:26.600 --> 07:31.606
and her accessories to do
is compose a new vision.

07:32.480 --> 07:35.723
That for me is creativity.

07:35.880 --> 07:37.689
Other people would say,
"Well, you know,

07:37.840 --> 07:39.604
it's just getting dressed,
and we all get dressed."

07:39.760 --> 07:41.683
Well, we all take snapshots
on our phone,

07:41.840 --> 07:43.490
and that doesn't make it art.

07:43.640 --> 07:45.563
The fact that she
combines everything,

07:45.720 --> 07:48.291
what is nice, what is ugly,
what's cheap, what is chic.

07:48.440 --> 07:51.330
So all these things,
and she just mixes that,

07:51.480 --> 07:53.209
and she makes
her own style of that,

07:53.360 --> 07:55.966
and that's really...
that's inspiration for me.

07:56.160 --> 07:59.130
Her things are so special.

07:59.280 --> 08:01.681
Everything Mrs. Apfel have
is gorgeous.

08:03.920 --> 08:07.322
When I first met her,
there were all kinds of people,

08:07.480 --> 08:10.882
all ages,
all walks of life,

08:11.040 --> 08:13.202
all surrounding her.

08:13.360 --> 08:16.409
She was so engaging
to everybody, you know?

08:16.600 --> 08:18.967
And I could feel the pulse
of her life,

08:19.120 --> 08:21.122
of her excitement
about living.

08:23.000 --> 08:25.048
This is Iris Apfel,

08:25.200 --> 08:29.125
and she is
a legendary collector,

08:29.320 --> 08:31.846
um, of fashion.

08:32.000 --> 08:33.650
Exhibits of her fashions
in museums

08:33.799 --> 08:36.451
like the Metropolitan Museum
of Art's Costume Institute

08:36.600 --> 08:38.409
drew record crowds.

08:38.559 --> 08:40.642
And that was in 2005.
I went.

08:40.799 --> 08:42.450
It was extraordinary.

08:42.600 --> 08:44.568
And tell us what you're wearing
right now, Iris.

08:44.720 --> 08:47.564
Oh, this actually
I bought many years ago

08:47.720 --> 08:49.165
for my darling husband,
and...

08:49.320 --> 08:50.446
You bought this shirt?

08:50.600 --> 08:53.171
Yeah,
this was done by Versace.

08:53.320 --> 08:55.607
He painted it himself.
It's leather.

08:55.800 --> 08:57.325
So I grabbed it,
and I took it home.

08:57.480 --> 09:00.131
And I gave it to him,
and he turned up his nose.

09:00.280 --> 09:01.611
And he said, "Oh..."

09:01.760 --> 09:04.047
lfis'husband
is sitting right here.

09:04.200 --> 09:06.282
Carl is sitting right
here in the front row.

09:07.640 --> 09:10.371
And Carl has pretty
fancy pants on.

09:10.520 --> 09:11.601
Look at those pants.

09:11.760 --> 09:13.091
They're from Etro.
I bought him those.

09:13.280 --> 09:15.009
- Oh, are those new?
- Yeah.

09:15.200 --> 09:18.044
Oh, okay. Very nice.
You're right with it, Carl.

09:18.240 --> 09:19.446
Thank you, dear.

09:30.120 --> 09:32.168
This goes back
to when the dinosaurs

09:32.320 --> 09:35.210
were roaming the Earth,
1948.

09:35.840 --> 09:38.764
Articles from The Times
and other newspapers.

09:43.080 --> 09:44.764
This is what
I looked like then.

09:49.680 --> 09:51.603
I never wanted a wedding.

09:51.760 --> 09:53.205
I wanted to elope.

09:53.400 --> 09:55.050
I said I'd rather have
the money.

09:56.720 --> 09:59.200
But the parents
and the grandparents

09:59.360 --> 10:01.124
wanted the wedding.

10:01.600 --> 10:04.490
Our first date
was Columbus Day.

10:05.320 --> 10:07.129
Thanksgiving, Carl proposed.

10:07.480 --> 10:09.721
Christmas, I got blinged.

10:11.040 --> 10:13.247
Washington's birthday,
we were married.

10:13.400 --> 10:16.051
Washington's birthday,
February 22nd.

10:16.800 --> 10:18.962
There was no
Presidents' Day then.

10:19.400 --> 10:22.722
It was a fairly small wedding,
I think 125 people.

10:22.880 --> 10:25.042
But very posh.

10:25.200 --> 10:29.285
The dress was pink lace,
and I'm really very practical,

10:29.480 --> 10:31.801
So I wanted a dress that
I could wear after the wedding

10:31.960 --> 10:33.962
and notjust put in a box.

10:34.120 --> 10:36.327
I still have these shoes

10:36.480 --> 10:40.804
sixty...
six and a half years later

10:40.960 --> 10:43.361
They were pale pink satin.

10:43.520 --> 10:45.204
They're back in style.

10:45.360 --> 10:48.330
If you hang around long enough,
everything comes back.

10:48.480 --> 10:53.247
This is ma and pa and moi.

10:53.400 --> 10:54.970
No siblings.

10:58.760 --> 11:01.969
There's Carl.
So gallant.

11:03.200 --> 11:05.282
There was something about her

11:05.440 --> 11:08.410
that just got into me.

11:08.840 --> 11:09.966
It's always there.

11:10.360 --> 11:12.488
Aw, my little pussycat.

11:13.080 --> 11:15.082
And I figured he was cool
and he was cuddly,

11:15.240 --> 11:18.050
and he cooked Chinese,
so I couldn't do any better.

11:34.560 --> 11:37.086
But it's been one trip,

11:37.240 --> 11:39.049
beautiful trip.

11:39.920 --> 11:41.729
I trained him well.

11:41.880 --> 11:44.645
And if she wants a child,
I'm it.

11:45.640 --> 11:47.210
He's a handful.

11:57.240 --> 12:01.131
The first piece I ever bought
was in Greenwich Village.

12:01.320 --> 12:06.451
I was about maybe 11,
12 years old.

12:06.960 --> 12:10.043
There was a little shop
in a basement

12:10.200 --> 12:12.407
of one of those old-fashioned
kind of tenement houses

12:12.560 --> 12:15.131
that had
the fire escapes outside,

12:16.080 --> 12:17.650
and I'll never forget
that place

12:17.840 --> 12:20.446
because I thought
it was Aladdin's cave.

12:20.600 --> 12:21.840
There was this little man.

12:22.000 --> 12:24.207
His name was Mr. Darris,

12:24.800 --> 12:27.087
and he was threadbare
but elegant.

12:29.240 --> 12:31.641
He always wore spats
and a monocle...

12:32.800 --> 12:34.848
and I always tell everybody
he treated me

12:35.000 --> 12:36.604
like I was a mini duchess.

12:36.760 --> 12:38.762
I'd come in,
and he never seen a kid

12:38.920 --> 12:40.922
be so interested
in all this junk before.

12:41.080 --> 12:42.923
I fixed on a brooch.

12:43.080 --> 12:45.686
I just thought
it was the cat's pajamas,

12:45.840 --> 12:47.763
and I really lusted
after that piece.

12:47.920 --> 12:50.810
So I finally saved up 65 cents,

12:50.960 --> 12:52.405
and we haggled a little bit
over the piece.

12:52.560 --> 12:53.891
I thought it'd be gone,

12:54.080 --> 12:56.048
but fortunately for me,
it was still there.

12:56.200 --> 12:58.771
Anyway, I bought it for
the magnificent sum of 65 cents.

12:58.960 --> 13:01.930
He gave it to me.
I was so thrilled, my God.

13:03.560 --> 13:04.607
You comfortable?

13:04.800 --> 13:06.962
Yeah, fine.
ls it hard for you to do this?

13:08.280 --> 13:09.327
Is it difficult?

13:09.480 --> 13:11.005
No, not at all.

13:11.840 --> 13:13.729
Honey, this is Harlem,
nothing's difficult.

13:16.240 --> 13:18.242
Now this is...
there's a lot of African stuff,

13:18.440 --> 13:20.681
- but the jewelry's great, Iris.
- Oh, let me see.

13:20.840 --> 13:22.922
- Shall we go in? Okay.
- Oh, absolutely.

13:25.760 --> 13:27.205
See, something white with...

13:27.360 --> 13:29.169
Yeah, those are all,
like, jackets.

13:29.320 --> 13:30.560
We'll go around there.

13:31.160 --> 13:32.844
I've always said that
the population of Harlem

13:33.040 --> 13:34.565
has much more style
than they do...

13:34.720 --> 13:36.324
downtown,
they think they're stylish,

13:36.480 --> 13:38.289
but they all were black,
you know?

13:38.440 --> 13:41.171
It's not really style.
It's a uniform.

13:41.320 --> 13:44.324
I used to come up here
on Sundays when I was a kid

13:44.480 --> 13:46.403
and watch all the ladies
going to church.

13:46.560 --> 13:47.607
Yeah, Sunday best.

13:47.720 --> 13:49.768
And they had real style,
I thought.

13:49.920 --> 13:51.763
And that sort of style
never goes out.

13:51.920 --> 13:55.242
No, no, but it doesn't exist
much anymore.

13:55.400 --> 13:57.209
But, you know, things change.

13:57.360 --> 13:59.442
I hope. I hope.
I try.

14:04.200 --> 14:06.168
- That's fun.
- The scarf?

14:06.360 --> 14:07.521
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

14:07.680 --> 14:09.250
That's like a scarf
or a belt.

14:09.400 --> 14:11.562
Oh, yeah.
How much?

14:11.720 --> 14:12.767
That's 45.

14:12.920 --> 14:14.410
That's a lot.

14:14.560 --> 14:17.450
Careful, Iris,
you're on "Candid Camera."

14:17.600 --> 14:19.011
I'm sorry, I'm cheap.

14:19.160 --> 14:22.403
No! You're not cheap.

14:23.280 --> 14:25.282
It's funny because
you find people think

14:25.440 --> 14:28.762
you just acquire things,
but actually, that's not you.

14:28.920 --> 14:30.251
No, it's hard work.

14:30.400 --> 14:32.289
You really have to put
a lot of effort into it.

14:32.440 --> 14:34.647
I know people who have
wonderful collections,

14:34.800 --> 14:36.404
but it's different.

14:36.600 --> 14:38.602
They go out to buy,
they go to...

14:38.760 --> 14:40.524
Auctions and things
like that, yeah.

14:40.680 --> 14:43.650
But everything I have,
I go out and find,

14:43.800 --> 14:45.802
- which is not easy.
- No.

14:45.960 --> 14:49.407
- I like that.
- That's beautiful.

14:49.560 --> 14:52.484
I like it.
The color, everything.

14:52.880 --> 14:54.723
So, monsieur,
how much are these ones?

14:54.880 --> 14:57.087
Okay, the bracelet ten.

14:57.240 --> 14:59.811
What I'll do, I'm going
to make you a deal.

15:00.000 --> 15:02.321
We know you, okay?

15:02.480 --> 15:07.327
Uh, take... I'll give you
$7 each for you.

15:07.480 --> 15:09.960
And what can you do
on the coat?

15:10.120 --> 15:13.169
The coat, we sell...
normal, we sell 125.

15:13.320 --> 15:14.651
But I'll
let you have it 100.

15:14.800 --> 15:16.962
- Okay.
- I know you.

15:17.120 --> 15:19.088
I know you, queen.
We know you.

15:19.240 --> 15:21.447
You can do better than 100.

15:23.560 --> 15:25.961
- And the bag?
- This 85.

15:26.120 --> 15:28.327
- Oh, you can do better.
- No, this 85.

15:28.480 --> 15:31.609
You see, the tanner
took one day to make it.

15:31.760 --> 15:35.207
- He's slow.
- Yeah. Yeah.

15:35.920 --> 15:38.082
How did you get that?
I can't get those prices.

15:38.240 --> 15:39.526
Oh, I'm very good.

15:39.680 --> 15:42.445
I know.
flaughs)

15:43.240 --> 15:45.846
Doing something creative,
taking your mind off things,

15:46.000 --> 15:48.765
but that's how you shop,
and that's how you dress,

15:48.920 --> 15:50.809
and that's how you think,
in that way.

15:50.960 --> 15:52.769
Oh, yes,
I mean, it's fun.

15:52.920 --> 15:55.651
Sometimes I really
don't feel well.

15:55.800 --> 15:58.326
And I get in there,
it's like I'm 19 1/2.

15:58.480 --> 16:01.689
I'm jumping around
and everything, and I'm so up.

16:01.840 --> 16:05.083
When I crawl back to the car...

16:05.240 --> 16:09.211
- I got my booty...
- How often do you need the fix?

16:09.400 --> 16:11.687
Oh, I'd like to have it
more often than I get it.

16:11.840 --> 16:13.205
Like how often, Iris,
once a week?

16:13.360 --> 16:15.488
- Oh, I would love it once a week.
- Yeah.

16:19.600 --> 16:22.490
I think what fascinates
me about Iris

16:22.640 --> 16:26.326
is that she's the perfect
example of the intersection

16:26.480 --> 16:30.530
of fashion
and interior design and art.

