51:02.840 --> 51:04.604
Well, for the window,
I guess I have a few pairs.

51:04.760 --> 51:06.171
I don't know how many I have.

51:06.320 --> 51:08.687
We were thinking we might
do this sort of thing.

51:08.840 --> 51:12.686
See it, Linda, the mask there?
Might do something like that.

51:13.240 --> 51:15.925
- This is a classic...
- I kind of like the glasses.

51:18.880 --> 51:20.609
The mannequins
could be holding something.

51:20.800 --> 51:23.041
I think it's a little chicer
just with glasses

51:23.200 --> 51:24.850
instead of with...
you know what I mean?

51:25.000 --> 51:27.048
We know it's Iris
just by the glasses.

51:27.200 --> 51:28.565
Let's just...

51:29.240 --> 51:30.685
but these would break, I guess.

51:30.840 --> 51:33.002
Here, I'm not going to
let go of them.

51:36.520 --> 51:39.046
Let's see the...
Let's try this girl here.

51:43.000 --> 51:44.684
Gee, I wonder who this is.

52:14.840 --> 52:16.729
The point of this
is just a little thing.

52:16.880 --> 52:19.770
I wanted to show sort of
all your different jobs,

52:19.920 --> 52:22.491
that you have
more jobs than anyone.

52:24.160 --> 52:27.164
Oh, I love that.
I love that.

52:28.600 --> 52:29.886
Isn't there sound?

52:30.080 --> 52:32.924
How do we tell the man
that there's no sound?

52:33.080 --> 52:34.570
Oh, okay, thanks.

52:35.240 --> 52:37.083
Can you start it over?

52:44.880 --> 52:46.530
We have something
really big for you

52:46.720 --> 52:48.006
- to surprise you with.
- For me?

52:48.160 --> 52:50.003
- Yes, absolutely.
- Oh, wow.

52:52.520 --> 52:55.205
There's some noise
coming from the bag.

52:56.120 --> 52:59.681
o“, my God! oh!

52:59.840 --> 53:02.002
So you can use this
to shop with you

53:02.160 --> 53:04.970
when you go to Whole Foods
to buy your forbidden rice.

53:05.160 --> 53:06.446
Oh, that's fabulous!

53:06.600 --> 53:09.251
- That's going to be in the stores.
- No.

53:09.400 --> 53:10.731
- Yeah.
- Big like this?

53:10.880 --> 53:13.406
- Big like this.
- Oh, Albert, look at that.

53:13.560 --> 53:16.325
- Oh, my God.
- We're excited about it.

53:16.480 --> 53:19.211
Oh.

53:19.360 --> 53:22.842
Oh, I can't believe it.
Oh, my God.

53:23.360 --> 53:24.850
I love you, Rory.

53:25.000 --> 53:27.731
You've been so kind
and gracious to me.

53:28.280 --> 53:29.566
My God.

53:29.720 --> 53:31.688
If somebody could
just open the door?

53:31.840 --> 53:33.251
I'll get it.

53:35.840 --> 53:38.081
I heard your other
collection is sold out.

53:38.240 --> 53:39.241
Sold out.

53:39.360 --> 53:42.125
Yeah, the Home Shopping.
Yeah, it was so exciting.

53:42.320 --> 53:44.687
Were you on it yourself
selling it?

53:44.840 --> 53:46.922
I was supposed to,
and I was in the hospital.

53:47.080 --> 53:49.321
Ijust had surgery.

53:49.960 --> 53:52.167
So they asked me
if I would talk,

53:52.320 --> 53:55.688
and I said yes,
and I summoned all my energy,

53:55.840 --> 53:57.046
and I did two shows.

53:57.200 --> 53:59.521
I guess it was about
half an hour each.

54:00.200 --> 54:03.602
And I was very...
You know, it was very exciting,

54:03.800 --> 54:06.326
and the next... for two days,
I couldn't get out of bed

54:06.480 --> 54:08.448
I was so drained.

54:08.640 --> 54:10.404
Carl doesn't know
I had hip surgery.

54:10.600 --> 54:12.329
He doesn't know
my hip was broken.

54:12.480 --> 54:14.687
Really?
How did you do that?

54:14.840 --> 54:16.365
Well, I didn't do it.
Nezzie did.

54:16.560 --> 54:18.528
Because Carl
is very devoted to me,

54:18.680 --> 54:20.808
particularly now that
he isn't feeling well,

54:20.960 --> 54:23.930
and she said if she was going
to stay with him,

54:24.080 --> 54:26.560
she couldn't tell him
because he'd go bananas.

54:26.720 --> 54:29.963
And he really was so upset
that I wasn't at home.

54:30.160 --> 54:31.889
- He knows I fell...
- Where did he think you were?

54:32.080 --> 54:33.366
No, he knows I fell.

54:33.520 --> 54:35.045
He was sleeping
when it happened.

54:35.200 --> 54:38.488
But when he got up...
what was I going to do?

54:38.640 --> 54:41.211
I was trying to wait
till the next day,

54:41.360 --> 54:44.921
but the head of NYU,
the head honcho

54:45.080 --> 54:46.844
is a good friend,
and he said, "You're crazy.

54:47.000 --> 54:48.240
You have to come immediately,

54:48.400 --> 54:50.129
and you have to come
in an ambulance."

54:50.840 --> 54:53.161
So I had to call the ambulance,
and I thought, "Oh, my God."

54:53.320 --> 54:54.765
But God was good,

54:54.920 --> 54:57.400
and they sent me
the two most delicious guys.

54:57.600 --> 55:00.843
They were big hunks, but they
were so sweet and so kind.

55:01.000 --> 55:04.721
And I explained the situation,
and they were, you know,

55:04.880 --> 55:07.690
kidding around
with Carl and whatnot,

55:07.840 --> 55:09.205
and they got me out.

55:09.360 --> 55:10.361
He thinks I fell...

55:10.520 --> 55:12.887
He knows I fell
and hurt my leg badly,

55:13.080 --> 55:14.081
but he doesn't know
I broke my hip.

55:14.240 --> 55:15.287
He doesn't know what happened.

55:15.440 --> 55:16.771
So we're always together.

55:16.920 --> 55:18.445
We work together
and everything else,

55:18.600 --> 55:20.284
so he's used
to having me around.

55:20.440 --> 55:23.603
He's older than I am,
well, so it was very sweet.

55:23.760 --> 55:25.205
You're very sweet together.

55:25.360 --> 55:26.521
<i>AnyWaY---</i>

55:34.800 --> 55:36.689
Have you met...
This is the Maysles crew.

55:36.840 --> 55:38.604
- No!
- I'm Katie.

55:38.760 --> 55:41.604
Katie, I'm Nancy.
Nice to meet you.

55:41.760 --> 55:44.206
- Sean.
- Sean, nice to meet you.

55:44.880 --> 55:47.167
And this is Albert Maysles
himself.

55:47.360 --> 55:49.886
Hello, Albert,
so nice to meet you.

55:50.040 --> 55:51.326
You want a nibble?
Help yourself.

55:51.480 --> 55:53.881
- Yes, yes.
- Albert, you want...

55:54.040 --> 55:56.042
I'm okay.
I had some breakfast.

55:56.200 --> 55:58.806
- Sweetie, you want some?
- We're okay, thank you.

55:59.000 --> 56:01.207
Greetings,
and welcome to the launch

56:01.360 --> 56:03.249
of the UT in NYC program.

56:03.400 --> 56:07.291
It is my pleasure
to introduce Mrs. Iris Apfel,

56:07.440 --> 56:09.204
our tour guide
and visiting professor

56:09.360 --> 56:11.203
for the week
in New York City.

56:11.360 --> 56:13.089
Mrs. Apfel?

56:13.240 --> 56:16.323
I have brought you
14 eager students

56:16.480 --> 56:18.050
from the University of Texas.

56:18.200 --> 56:19.964
Good, well, I don't want
to waste any time

56:20.120 --> 56:22.282
because we have
a lot of things to do.

56:22.480 --> 56:25.848
And the reason I chose this
was because I've had occasion

56:26.000 --> 56:28.446
in the last couple of years
to work with students,

56:28.600 --> 56:31.524
which I never did before,
and I find that, unhappily,

56:31.680 --> 56:33.921
they may be very well-trained
in their craft,

56:34.080 --> 56:36.970
but they haven't got a clue
as to the outside world.

56:38.320 --> 56:40.482
So the sage has spoken.

56:47.280 --> 56:49.760
Everybody faints
when they hear the itinerary

56:49.920 --> 56:51.763
because it's really...
I must say,

56:51.920 --> 56:55.402
they're all offbeat fields
like licensing and styling

56:55.560 --> 56:58.086
and things that kids
don't think about as fashion.

56:58.240 --> 56:59.890
They just think
it's not glamorous,

57:00.040 --> 57:01.769
but it's important.

57:01.920 --> 57:05.288
I mean, all the great
handcrafted trades

57:05.480 --> 57:06.606
are going down the tubes.

57:06.760 --> 57:08.489
Some have already gone.

57:09.120 --> 57:10.929
And then there's nobody left
to teach them,

57:11.080 --> 57:15.085
and you'll have all kinds
of machine-made junk.

57:15.280 --> 57:18.489
Listen up, everybody,
this wonderful, wonderful man

57:18.640 --> 57:20.290
is going to talk with you.

57:20.440 --> 57:23.762
He is in my opinion,
and I think not only mine

57:23.960 --> 57:26.964
but everybody else's,
the king of the runway,

57:27.120 --> 57:29.043
and he comes
from a long tradition

57:29.200 --> 57:31.328
of embroiderers and beaders.

57:31.480 --> 57:33.767
So listen, he's going to
tell you wonderful things.

57:33.920 --> 57:37.811
You have to keep your eyes open
for anything and everything.

57:37.960 --> 57:42.409
Like me flying, going to Miami,
I look down from the plane,

57:42.600 --> 57:45.206
and I see fields of...
you know, fields.

57:45.360 --> 57:47.567
It looked like a...
like an amazing pattern.

57:47.720 --> 57:50.769
I drew it up,
and it's in one of my dresses.

57:50.920 --> 57:53.446
Now it's up to you
as a designer.

57:54.320 --> 57:56.049
What are you inspired by?

57:56.240 --> 57:58.322
And I think
whatever feeds you...

57:58.480 --> 57:59.686
You could be curious about math,

57:59.840 --> 58:01.001
you could be curious
about science,

58:01.200 --> 58:02.406
you could be curious
about fashion,

58:02.560 --> 58:03.721
you could be curious
about anything,

58:03.880 --> 58:05.769
but ultimately, what drives you
and makes you better

58:05.960 --> 58:07.325
is learning something
you don't already know.

58:07.480 --> 58:09.767
I could never be
a good friend of anybody

58:09.960 --> 58:12.247
who wasn't curious or didn't
have a sense of humor.

58:12.400 --> 58:15.210
I think those are the two great
gifts that I got in my cradle.

58:15.360 --> 58:16.407
I really believe that.

58:16.560 --> 58:19.484
People always love enthusiasm,
and I think that, in the end,

58:19.680 --> 58:22.411
New York is about work
and getting a job done.

58:22.600 --> 58:25.080
So it's great if you're
a cute girl in a cute dress

58:25.240 --> 58:27.481
and want to be
on the red carpet, but really,

58:27.640 --> 58:30.291
if you mean business,
New York is the place for you.

58:30.480 --> 58:31.481
If you mean business,

58:31.560 --> 58:33.289
people will
take you seriously, I think.

58:34.120 --> 58:36.771
It's very important to me
that my program continue.

58:36.920 --> 58:39.082
It's going gangbusters.

58:39.280 --> 58:43.729
The kids are now fighting to get
in, and the school shows no...

58:43.880 --> 58:46.326
I mean, unless it falls
by the wayside

58:46.480 --> 58:48.164
and they can't get
anymore funding...

58:48.320 --> 58:50.402
I mean,
I can't do this forever,

58:50.560 --> 58:52.324
but I'm sure they'll be able
to get somebody else.

58:52.480 --> 58:53.925
Awesome, thank you.

58:58.240 --> 59:00.447
You never had children.

59:00.640 --> 59:02.369
No, we never wanted to.

59:03.080 --> 59:04.730
I mean, not that I...
but you can't...

59:04.880 --> 59:07.804
I learned a long time ago you
can't have everything,

59:07.960 --> 59:11.009
and I wanted a career,
and I wanted to travel,

59:11.160 --> 59:13.527
and my mother...
I know how much I resented it.

59:13.680 --> 59:15.682
She had stopped for a while,

59:15.840 --> 59:18.491
and then when I was like ten
or 11, she went back,

59:18.640 --> 59:22.850
and I was very upset.
Very upset.

59:23.000 --> 59:24.650
I felt I was...
I mean, it was stupid,

59:24.800 --> 59:26.404
but I felt I was being
abandoned,

59:26.560 --> 59:31.248
so I said I didn't want to have
my child raised by a nanny.

59:31.400 --> 59:34.290
And you can't do everything.
It's impossible.

59:34.800 --> 59:36.484
Something has to give.

59:37.240 --> 59:38.890
And sometimes it's you.

59:43.000 --> 59:46.288
Well, I haven't had a
chance to go through anything.

59:46.440 --> 59:47.521
Yes.

59:47.680 --> 59:49.284
Logistics, logistics.

59:53.120 --> 59:54.804
Okay. There we go.

59:56.200 --> 59:58.771
Galliano's pieces
are fantastic.

59:58.920 --> 01:00:00.524
Yes.

01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:05.247
This is spectacular.

01:00:06.120 --> 01:00:10.125
The Peabody Essex Museum
hosted Iris' exhibition

01:00:10.280 --> 01:00:13.363
"The Rare Bird of Fashion"
in, um...

01:00:13.520 --> 01:00:14.646
'09.

01:00:15.080 --> 01:00:18.004
And then when the
exhibition came to the museum,

01:00:18.160 --> 01:00:19.730
we invited Iris and Carl,
of course,

01:00:19.880 --> 01:00:22.360
to be part
of the installation.

01:00:22.520 --> 01:00:25.842
And so I learned
that Peabody

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:29.447
had a fashion collection,
but it more or less stopped

01:00:29.640 --> 01:00:31.369
at the time that mine begins.

01:00:31.960 --> 01:00:34.406
So we decided
that it would be a nice fit,

01:00:34.560 --> 01:00:37.245
and that I would,
little by little,

01:00:37.440 --> 01:00:39.886
give all the stuff
to the museum.

01:00:40.040 --> 01:00:42.042
So we started last year.

01:00:42.240 --> 01:00:43.890
They got 80-odd pieces
last year.

01:00:44.040 --> 01:00:45.121
Yes, mm-hmm.

01:00:45.200 --> 01:00:48.727
Probably get another batch,
and will keep going.

01:00:48.880 --> 01:00:52.601
Oh, those are trousers.
Oh, look at that.

01:00:53.040 --> 01:00:55.441
Oh, with a matching coat.

01:00:58.920 --> 01:01:01.526
What an interesting
color combination.

01:01:01.720 --> 01:01:03.563
This is a very personal
collection.

01:01:03.760 --> 01:01:07.207
This is mine, and I didn't
buy it to impress anybody.

01:01:07.360 --> 01:01:09.362
I bought it
because I liked it.

01:01:09.560 --> 01:01:11.722
And I wore almost everything.

01:01:13.560 --> 01:01:15.881
Some things I wore to pieces.

01:01:16.040 --> 01:01:18.247
This is the green...
This is the green one.

01:01:18.440 --> 01:01:23.207
I was collecting
church vestments at one point.

01:01:23.360 --> 01:01:27.126
So with this one,
I found a pair.

01:01:27.280 --> 01:01:29.965
I took the pair,
and I cut it apart,

01:01:30.160 --> 01:01:32.128
and I made a pair of trousers.

01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:35.651
- This has a number.
- What is that?

01:01:35.800 --> 01:01:38.041
It's a black, white,
or blue...

01:01:38.200 --> 01:01:40.407
- With fringe.
- Oh, no, it's dark blue.

01:01:40.560 --> 01:01:43.723
Oh, that's a gorgeous fabric.
That is a fabric to die for.

01:01:43.880 --> 01:01:48.522
Yeah, as if there aren't other
to-die-for fabrics here.

01:01:48.720 --> 01:01:49.801
But this one is very...

01:01:49.960 --> 01:01:51.041
But it's interesting
to see which ones

01:01:51.200 --> 01:01:53.282
you get really excited about.

01:01:54.320 --> 01:01:55.367
Look at this.

01:01:55.560 --> 01:01:57.722
- Oh, wow.
- It's woven.

01:01:57.880 --> 01:02:00.042
It's a velvet
and then the lace, wow.

01:02:00.520 --> 01:02:01.851
It's quite the combination.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:04.844
But look at how it's threaded
up through with the fringe.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:07.287
Where did you find this?
Here or...

01:02:07.440 --> 01:02:10.284
No, you' don't find
anything like this here.

01:02:10.440 --> 01:02:13.842
Somebody once told me,
and it's so true,

01:02:14.040 --> 01:02:15.565
you really don't own
anything while you're here.

01:02:15.720 --> 01:02:17.609
You just rent,
so sometimes,

01:02:17.760 --> 01:02:19.967
it might be nicer to
see where it's going

01:02:20.120 --> 01:02:23.841
than to not know who gets it,
so I'm happy to do it.

01:02:37.840 --> 01:02:40.241
How do you choose
what to give away?

01:02:40.440 --> 01:02:42.442
It's not easy.

01:02:42.600 --> 01:02:44.443
Does it keep you up?

01:02:45.360 --> 01:02:47.203
Oh, God, no.

01:02:49.200 --> 01:02:52.727
No, I have more important things
to keep me up at night.

01:02:52.880 --> 01:02:54.325
No, no.

01:02:54.480 --> 01:02:56.403
Well,
now I have to ask what...

01:02:56.560 --> 01:02:58.130
What keeps you up at night?

01:02:59.160 --> 01:03:01.083
Oh, I mean...

01:03:02.240 --> 01:03:04.925
Matters of health
and things like that.

01:03:06.320 --> 01:03:07.606
Things
that are really important.

01:03:07.800 --> 01:03:09.131
Mm-hmm.

01:03:11.360 --> 01:03:12.771
I mean, as you get older,
you realize

01:03:12.920 --> 01:03:15.127
that all these other things
are just...

01:03:25.840 --> 01:03:27.729
Iris,
just looking over here?

01:03:32.400 --> 01:03:35.051
How many people have been
in here before, Iris?

01:03:35.200 --> 01:03:37.328
Not too many.
I don't let anybody in here.

01:03:37.480 --> 01:03:39.642
Trying to get it
a little organized.

01:03:40.480 --> 01:03:41.606
Great.

01:03:42.040 --> 01:03:43.724
Uaughs)

01:03:46.040 --> 01:03:47.485
Great.

01:03:48.560 --> 01:03:50.244
Do you want me
to hang this somewhere?

01:03:50.400 --> 01:03:51.925
- Just stick it here.
- Okay.

01:03:52.080 --> 01:03:54.845
I have two more hangars
of items.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:56.206
Thank you.

01:04:00.120 --> 01:04:02.964
It's a system until a lot
of people stick their noses in,

01:04:03.120 --> 01:04:05.726
and then it gets
all fucked up.

01:04:07.760 --> 01:04:08.886
Put it here.

01:04:09.040 --> 01:04:11.520
Okay, and then
this J. Crew dress.

01:04:11.680 --> 01:04:13.284
- Put it here.
- Okay.

01:04:14.360 --> 01:04:15.441
Look at that coat.

01:04:15.600 --> 01:04:18.046
Hi.
How are you?

01:04:18.200 --> 01:04:19.440
My beautiful child.

01:04:19.600 --> 01:04:20.840
How are you, pussycat?

01:04:27.560 --> 01:04:28.561
I made it.

01:04:28.760 --> 01:04:31.843
Are you all right?
Are you okay?

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:33.490
I don't know.

01:04:33.680 --> 01:04:35.648
Somebody's stealing my breath.

01:04:35.800 --> 01:04:38.929
Be quiet.
Relax, relax, relax.

01:04:44.600 --> 01:04:47.524
What's that cousin's name
with two kids up there?

01:04:47.680 --> 01:04:51.162
Carl, just relax.
Don't talk.

01:04:52.040 --> 01:04:53.690
Catch your breath.

01:04:54.280 --> 01:04:55.850
My aunt rarely relaxes,

01:04:56.000 --> 01:04:58.571
and I think that's kind
of a fault on occasion.

01:04:58.720 --> 01:05:02.327
I think sometimes she should
slow down, and I ask her,

01:05:02.480 --> 01:05:04.960
or I kind of even insist,
that she do a little bit,

01:05:05.120 --> 01:05:07.691
rests a little bit more,
but it's not her personality.

01:05:07.880 --> 01:05:09.644
She's even said
that when she's not busy,

01:05:09.840 --> 01:05:11.080
she can get depressed.

01:05:11.240 --> 01:05:12.651
She's not at all
a depressive person,

01:05:12.840 --> 01:05:14.444
but I can understand
that her personality

01:05:14.600 --> 01:05:17.524
is to keep moving,
keep busy, keep occupied,

01:05:17.720 --> 01:05:20.769
keep creative, keep productive,
and that's her life,

01:05:20.920 --> 01:05:22.649
and it has always been
her life.

01:05:30.640 --> 01:05:32.244
Oh, I like being active.

01:05:32.400 --> 01:05:34.243
I like being in the world
and of the world,

01:05:34.400 --> 01:05:37.483
and everybody has to do it
in his or her own way.

01:05:37.640 --> 01:05:39.847
I think I told you this
about my mother's friend.

01:05:40.040 --> 01:05:42.202
When you would say,
"How are you feeling today?"

01:05:42.360 --> 01:05:44.249
She'd say,
"Well, to tell you the truth,

01:05:44.400 --> 01:05:46.687
when I get up in the morning,
